otes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n\n'''St. Anthony''', also known as '''Saint Anthony Village''', is a city in [[Hennepin County, Minnesota|Hennepin]] and [[Ramsey County, Minnesota|Ramsey]] counties in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Minnesota]]. At the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] the population was 8,226,<ref name=\"2010 Census (County Subs)\">{{cite web|title=2010 Census Redistricting Data (Public Law 94-171) Summary File \u2013 County Subdivision|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST16&prodType=table|work=American FactFinder|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=1 May 2011}}{{dead link|bot=medic|date=April 2020}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> of whom 5,156 lived in the larger Hennepin County part of the city<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US270535668056680| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): St. Anthony city (part), St. Anthony city, Hennepin County, Minnesota| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 28, 2015| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214000941/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US270535668056680| archive-date=February 14, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> and 3,070 in the Ramsey County part.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US271235668056680| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): St. Anthony city (part), St. Anthony city, Ramsey County, Minnesota| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=September 28, 2015| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214000745/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/0700000US271235668056680| archive-date=February 14, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> The city is run by a five-member council consisting of a mayor and four council members who serve four-year terms.\n\nSt. Anthony was also the name of [[Minneapolis]]'s older twin city, across from downtown Minneapolis on the Mississippi River's east bank. Minneapolis and St. Anthony merged in 1872. There is also a city named [[St. Anthony, Stearns County, Minnesota|St. Anthony]] in [[Stearns County, Minnesota|Stearns County]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:StAnthonysign.jpg|left|thumb|Signage to the city]]\nSt. Anthony's origins date to 1838, when [[Franklin Steele]], a storekeeper at [[Fort Snelling]], made a claim on the land east of [[St. Anthony Falls]]. Steele did not begin developing the land until 1848, but it quickly became a center of milling and trade much like the neighboring town of Minneapolis on the land west of the falls. In 1858 the town was formally organized as the Township of St. Anthony.<ref>{{cite web| title=Early St. Anthony and Minneapolis| url=http://www.mnhs.org/places/safhb/history_early.php| website=St. Anthony Falls Heritage Board}}</ref>\n\nIn 1872, Minneapolis annexed most of St. Anthony (much of present-day [[Northeast, Minneapolis|Northeast Minneapolis]]). Roughly {{convert|1000|acre}} of mostly agricultural land north of the city retained the name St. Anthony but remained unincorporated. In 1945, the township's residents voted 167\u201357 in favor of incorporating as a village. The state challenged this decision on the basis that St. Anthony was too agricultural and rural, but it was upheld by the [[Minnesota Supreme Court]]. As the city's suburbs grew outward, St. Anthony evolved from a rural township to an [[inner suburb]].<ref>{{cite web| title=St. Anthony History| url=http://www.ci.saint-anthony.mn.us/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC={D5B9ACE3-BD0C-47FC-BF54-75188969A419}&DE={11517D69-FE5F-4FAA-8299-54CED52EBCD8}| website=City of St. Anthony}}</ref>\n\nSt. Anthony was the home of [[Apache Plaza]], the tenth indoor shopping mall in United States, which opened in October 1961. The second oldest, [[Southdale Center|Southdale]], lay only {{convert|15|mi}} to the south and was completed in October 1956. Built in the 1950s, the St. Anthony Shopping Center was Minnesota's first [[strip mall]] and was owned by the [[Fulgencio Batista|Batista]] family of Cuba.<ref>[http://www.ci.saint-anthony.mn.us/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=%7B3BD572E6-22A4-4493-AFE2-F0C21F7402D7%7D St. Anthony \u2013 Did You Know?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2006, the [[St. Anthony Village High School]] Huskies claimed ISD 282's first state baseball championship. The Huskies won the championship again in 2008. The school has also won five Class AA state championships in [[Minnesota State Knowledge Bowl Meet|Knowledge Bowl]] and has won one Minnesota Science Bowl competition. \n\n==Geography==\nSt. Anthony is {{convert|4|mi|0}} northeast of downtown Minneapolis. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.37|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|2.25|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.12|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64vfLAeJ2?url=http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-01-24}}</ref>\n\nOne of St. Anthony's longest and most widely used streets is Silver Lake Road. Named for Silver Lake in the northwest part of the city, it runs the length of St. Anthony from north to south. County Highway 88 is another of the city's main routes. [[Interstate 35W (Minnesota)|Interstate 35W]] skims through the south near the St. Anthony Boulevard exit.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1850= 656\n|1860= 265\n|1870= 236\n|1880= 485\n|1890= 92\n|1900= 93\n|1910= 100\n|1920= 134\n|1930= 455\n|1940= 607\n|1950= 1406\n|1960= 5084\n|1970= 9239\n|1980= 7981\n|1990= 7727\n|2000= 8012\n|2010= 8226\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=9066\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=August 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|author=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref><br>2013 Estimate<ref name=\"2013 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Population Estimates|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2013/SUB-EST2013-3.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2014-07-14}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the 2010 [[census]],<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref> there were 8,226 people, 3,848 households, and 2,054 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|3656.0|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 4,098 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1821.3|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 85.1% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 5.0% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.6% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 5.9% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.0% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 2.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.9% of the population.\n\nThere were 3,848 households of which 21.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 46.6% were non-families. 39.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 19.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.83.\n\nThe median age in the city was 43.1 years. 17.5% of residents were under the age of 18; 8.5% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 26.1% were from 25 to 44; 26.4% were from 45 to 64; and 21.4% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 46.1% male and 53.9% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], there were 8,012 people, 3,697 households, and 2,007 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 3,513.8 people per square mile (1,356.8/km\u00b2).  There were 3,812 housing units at an average density of 1,671.8 per square mile (645.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 90.58% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 2.06% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.64% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.51% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.79% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.41% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.65% of the population. 20.5% were of [[Germans|German]], 12.6% [[Norwegians|Norwegian]], 10.5% [[Swedish people|Swedish]], 8.7% [[Poles|Polish]] and 6.3% [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry.\n\nThere were 3,697 households out of which 20.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 44.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.7% were non-families. 38.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 18.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.83.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 18.0% under the age of 18, 8.9% from 18 to 24, 26.2% from 25 to 44, 21.9% from 45 to 64, and 25.1% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 85.2 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $46,883, and the median income for a family was $62,500. Males had a median income of $43,043 versus $31,304 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $26,290.  About 2.8% of families and 5.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 5.0% of those under age 18 and 3.0% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:StAnthonySchool.jpg|right|thumb|St. Anthony Middle/High School]]\nSt. Anthony is served by the [[St. Anthony-New Brighton School District]], ISD 282. Wilshire Park Elementary School is the district's primary school. St. Anthony Middle School serves grades 6\u20138. [[St. Anthony Village High School]] serves grades 9\u201312. St. Charles Borromeo offers private education for grades K\u20138.\n\n==Parks and recreation==\nSt. Anthony has several city parks. The most notable is Central Park, in the center of the city near the High School and Community Center, as well as the police station, fire station and water treatment plant. Several of the high school's athletic teams host home competitions in Central Park. Smaller parks include Emerald Park, Silver Point Park, and Trillium Park. St. Anthony also has a golf course maintained by the Minneapolis Parks and Recreation Board and a county park, [[Three Rivers Park District#Silverwood Park|Silverwood]], maintained by the [[Three Rivers Park District]].<ref>Francis Gross Golf Course. Minneapolis Parks and Recreation Board. http://minneapolisparks.org/default.asp?PageID=94&parkid=293. Accessed December 28, 2007.</ref><ref>Silverwood.  Three Rivers Park District. http://www.threeriversparkdistrict.org/parks/silverwood.cfm. Accessed December 28, 2007.</ref> Silverwood Park is on [[Silver Lake (Minneapolis)|Silver Lake]], which is almost entirely within St. Anthony's boundaries.\n\n==Sister city==\nSt. Anthony Village has one [[town twinning|sister city]], as designated by [[Sister Cities International]]:\n\n*{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Salo, Finland]]\n\nSt. Anthony dedicated Salo Park to its sister city on June 8, 2006, in its [[Silver Lake Village]] development.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tim Vakoc|H. Timothy (\"Tim\") Vakoc]], former associate pastor of St. Charles Borromeo Catholic Church in St. Anthony, and the first U.S. military chaplain to die from wounds received in the [[Iraq War]]\n* [[Shooting of Philando Castile]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ci.saint-anthony.mn.us Saint Anthony Village official website]\n\n{{Hennepin County, Minnesota}}\n{{Ramsey County, Minnesota}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Anthony, Minnesota}}\n[[Category:Cities in Hennepin County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Cities in Ramsey County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Cities in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1861]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the unrelated city in Stearns County|St. Anthony, Stearns County, Minnesota}}\n{{short description|City in Minnesota, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = City of St. Anthony\n|other_name               = ''Saint Anthony Village''\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = The Village<ref name=\"citywebsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.saint-anthony.mn.us/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=88444830-5166-4C25-8209-F597BCD70EA4|title=About St. Anthony|author=City of St. Anthony}}</ref>\n|motto                    = \"A Village Within the City\"<ref name=\"citywebsite\" />\n|image_skyline            = StAnthonyShopping.jpg\n|imagesize                = 300px\n|image_caption            = New urbanism on the site of former Apache Plaza \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = Hennepin_County_Minnesota_Incorporated_